 politics returned to historical norms: new parties shake up the system but are eventually absorbed into it, bringing innovation but not transformation. You can’t understand modern Canadian politics without understanding the 1993 election.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCoalition governmentszCanada. 0aPolitical partieszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aBaier, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarty, R. Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311141763940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486704740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774867047423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774867047/original  a978-3-11-127214-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-127419-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-141763-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles